                      @{"Imponance factor - what is it?" LINK WhatIsIt}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "WhatIsIt"

Imponance factor is the unit that measure how cool something looks, it has
nothing to do with how smart or usable something is, just looks. It is
derived from the swedish word 'imponans' (known only to a few lucky ones).
With this program you can increase your imponance factor by several
percent.

jAnimator is a program that will enable you to have animated images on
your workbench. It is also possible to configure the program so that a
program is started if you click on the image.

Features:
· Handles transparent images and alpha channels
· Supports image (and animation) scaling with possible (slow) high quality
  or fast low quality (same type as ImageFX uses).
· Uses datatypes or built in IFF-ILBM loader to load images or animations
· Can load a series of pictures and use them as an animation
· Can load a series of animations also
· Can load and save animations in a simple but fast special format for
  maximum performance
· Comes with a nice boing ball animation!
· Fully localized
· A commodity

The boingball animation was created by me in PovRay. The 

                            @{"System requirements" LINK SystemRequirements}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "SystemRequirements"

To run jAnimator you need Cybergraphics 3 (I can't really know which
version is required because the documentation doesn't mention which version
each function call needs) and at least AmigaOS2.0. To use datatypes you
will need OS3.0 and to start workbench programs you need OS3.5 or you can
use WBLoad (check Aminet or magazine CDs).

To load animations directly (gif-animations for example) you have to have
at least OS3.5 and a picture datatype that supports multiple pictures in a
picture file. OS3.5 comes with such GIF-datatype.

                               @{"Installation" LINK Installation}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Installation"

Install the program by using the provided installer script.

                               @{"How to use it" LINK HowToUseIt}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "HowToUseIt"

The program can be started from Workbench or CLI. The tooltypes match the
CLI arguments.

It is possible to make project icons with the default tool as jAnimator. In
that case only the tooltypes in the project icon will be used. It is also
possible to change the tooltypes in the tool icon (jAnimator itself).
___________________________________________________________________________

The CLI-arguments are:

@{"FILE/A" LINK Arg_File}
@{"MULTIPLE/S" LINK Arg_Multiple}
@{"X=XPOS/K/N" LINK Arg_Xpos}
@{"Y=YPOS/K/N" LINK Arg_Ypos}
@{"RIGHT/S" LINK Arg_Right}
@{"BOTTOM/S" LINK Arg_Bottom}
@{"W=WIDTH/K/N" LINK Arg_Width}
@{"H=HEIGHT/K/N" LINK Arg_Height}
@{"SIZE/K/N" LINK Arg_Size}
@{"ACCURATE/S" LINK Arg_Accurate}
@{"T=TRANSPARENT/S" LINK Arg_Transparent}
@{"R=RED/K/N" LINK Arg_Red}
@{"G=GREEN/K/N" LINK Arg_Green}
@{"B=BLUE/K/N" LINK Arg_Blue}
@{"ALPHA/K/N" LINK Arg_Alpha}
@{"PUBSCREEN/K" LINK Arg_PubScreen}
@{"DELAY/K/N" LINK Arg_Delay}
@{"SPEED/K/N" LINK Arg_Speed}
@{"TASKPRI/K/N" LINK Arg_TaskPri}
@{"CLI=EXECUTECLI/K" LINK Arg_ExecuteCLI}
@{"WB=EXECUTEWB/K" LINK Arg_ExecuteWB}
@{"SAVEFILE/K" LINK Arg_SaveFile}
@{"CX_PRIORITY/K/N" LINK Arg_Priority}

___________________________________________________________________________

Examples:

	jAnimator Boingball.argb

Loads the animation "Boingball.argb" and displays it in the center of the
default public screen.

	jAnimator Comic01.iff MULTIPLE TRANSPARENT RED=255 GREEN=255 BLUE=255

Loads the pictures "Comic01.iff", "Comic02.iff", ... and makes the white
color transparent.

	jAnimator Boingball.argb SIZE=50 ACCURATE RIGHT XPOS=0 BOTTOM
	YPOS=0 PUBSCREEN=Internet

Loads the animation "Boingball.argb", rescales it accurately to half size and
displays it in the bottom right corner of the public screen named "Internet".

	jAnimator Flower.iff XPOS=0 YPOS=11 ALPHA=20
	EXECUTEWB="Miami:MiamiDx"

Loads the picture "Flower.iff" and displays it hardly visible in the upper
left corner of the screen. Clicking on it starts the Workbench program
MiamiDx (located in "Miami:").
___________________________________________________________________________

Exit jAnimator by sending a ctrl-c to the program or by using the
commodities exchange utility.

                                  @{"History" LINK History}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Arg_File"

FILE: [string] [required]

This is the (first) filename and path to the picture or animation to display.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Multiple"

MULTIPLE: [switch]

Enabling this switch tells the program to try to load several numbered pictures (or
animations) and add all of them to the final animation. All pictures and
animations will be scaled to fit the size of the first picture or animation
unless SIZE, WIDTH or HEIGHT has been used to override that.

Picture name examples:

If the picture file is Pic00, the program will try to load Pic01, Pic02,...
If the picture file is Pic_a, the program will try to load Pic_b, Pic_c,...
If the picture file is P89.p, the program will try to load P90.p, P91.p,...

That is, the first thing found before a file name extension will be
increased. Note however that the program will not add characters to the
name so after 'pic9' the program will try to load 'pid0' which may seem
confusing. I don't see that as a major problem so it will stay that way
until someone convinces me that it is.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Xpos"

XPOS: [number]

This is the desired left horizontal position (in pixels) of the picture or
animation on the screen. If the @{"RIGHT" LINK Arg_Right} switch is set then this is calculated
from the right instead. The default is centered horizontally.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Ypos"

YPOS: [number]

This is the desired top vertical position (in pixels) of the picture or
animation on the screen. If the @{"BOTTOM" LINK Arg_Bottom} switch is set then this is
calculated from the bottom instead. The default is centered vertically.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Right"

RIGHT: [switch]

This switch tells the program to calculate the horizontal position from the
right instead of the default - from the left.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Bottom"

BOTTOM: [switch]

This switch tells the program to calculate the vertical position from the
bottom instead of the default - from the top.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Width"

WIDTH: [number]

This is the desired picture width. The pictures or animations loaded will be
scaled to fit this width.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Height"

HEIGHT: [number]

This is the desired picture height. The pictures or animations loaded will be
scaled to fit this height.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Size"

SIZE: [number]

This is the desired display size in percentage of the first loaded picture.
The pictures or animations loaded will be scaled to fit this size. Example
SIZE=50 will force the image or animation to be scaled down to half size.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Accurate"

ACCURATE: [switch]

This switch enables the accurate scaling algoritm. This is much more
accurate than the normal scaling algorithm but takes much more time. I
recommend that you use this if you shrink an image or animation but not if
you enlarge one since it is too accurate. I also recommend that you save
the scaled animation and use that one instead, since that is much faster to
load. Scaling down pictures before saving them will give them a much
smoother edge since the alpha channel is scaled too.

ImageFX uses the simple algorithm (or at least something like it) so if you
are happy with that, you don't have to use accurate. The better quality is
best shown when scaling down something with sharp edges down to a size not
50%, 25%, 12.5% (and so on) of the original image.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Transparent"

TRANSPARENT: [switch]

This switch enables a transparent background color. The red, green and blue
values of the color that should be transparent should be specified with the
@{"RED" LINK Arg_Red}, @{"GREEN" LINK Arg_Green} and @{"BLUE" LINK Arg_Blue} arguments, else black will be transparent.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Red"

RED: [number]

This is the (8-bit) red color value of the transparent color. You may use
numbers from 0 to 255. The default value is 0. See also @{"TRANSPARENT" LINK Arg_Transparent}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Green"

GREEN: [number]

This is the (8-bit) green color value of the transparent color. You may use
numbers from 0 to 255. The default value is 0. See also @{"TRANSPARENT" LINK Arg_Transparent}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Blue"

BLUE: [number]

This is the (8-bit) blue color value of the transparent color. You may use
numbers from 0 to 255. The default value is 0. See also @{"TRANSPARENT" LINK Arg_Transparent}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Alpha"

ALPHA: [number]

This can alter the opaqueness of the image or animation. You may use
numbers from 0 to 255. 255 means a fully visible animation and 0 means
totally invisible. The default value is 255.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_PubScreen"

PUBSCREEN: [string]

This selects the public screen that the animation is supposed to exist on.
The default is "Workbench".

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Delay"

DELAY: [number]

This sets how many 1/50 seconds the program should wait after loading the
animation before actually begin to animate it. The default is 0.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Speed"

SPEED: [number]

This will configure the delay in milliseconds (1/1000 seconds) between each
picture in the animation. The default is 20, which means that the animation
will run in 50 frames per second assuming that the processor can keep up
with the drawing.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_TaskPri"

TASKPRI: [number]

This sets that taskpriority of the program. The default is -1 which will
keep force the program to not steal any processor time from any ordinary
tasks. This is not always desired. For maximum imponance factor this value
should be changed to at least 1, then starting programs won't affect the
smoothness of the animation.

Also, it is recommended to install MagicMenu to increase the imponance
factor, since that it doesn't hog all graphic output on the screen while
holding the right mouse button that the Workbench menus does.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_ExecuteCLI"

EXECUTECLI: [string]

This is the CLI-program that will be executed when the animation is
clicked. If it is not set, then the animation can be dragged around with
the mouse.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_ExecuteWB"

EXECUTEWB: [string]

This is the Workbench program (with path) that will be executed when the
animation is clicked. If it is not set, then the animation can be dragged
around with the mouse.

Note that this feature can only be used if you have AmigaOS3.5 installed.
If you haven't, I suggest you get hold on the free program WBLoad that will
make it possible to start Workbench programs from CLI.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_SaveFile"

SAVEFILE: [string]

This is the filename to save the loaded animation pictures to. This can be
used to merge a lot of pictures or animations into a single file that will
load considerably faster since all scaling is done before it is saved.
Also, it is saved in an uncompressed format tailored for this program.

Note that the alpha channel is also saved so any transparency will be in
the original pictures as well as any other transparent color specified with
the @{"TRANSPARENT" LINK Arg_Transparent} tooltype/CLI-argument. Additional transparent colors can be
set by reloading and saving the animation again with the @{"TRANSPARENT" LINK Arg_Transparent}
tooltype/CLI-argument set.

Also, the @{"SPEED" LINK Arg_Speed} value is saved so it will be replayed with the original
speed (the @{"SPEED" LINK Arg_Speed} tooltype/CLI-argument overrides this).

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arg_Priority"

CX_PRIORITY: [number]

This is the priority of the commodity broker that jAnimator installs. The
default value is 0.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "History"

v1.0  (14.6.2000)
      Initial release

                                   @{"Bugs" LINK Bugs}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Bugs"

jAnimator doesn't load animations with the animation datatype. Instead it
uses the special feature of the OS3.5 picture datatype that makes it
possible to load several pictures from one picture file (animation). It can
at least handle the popular GIF animation format.

When demo animations has been installed in the WBStartup drawer, it may
happen that the transparent colors are wrong once the background picture has
loaded. It is necessary for jAnimator to not draw anything until the
background picture has loaded. Increase the @{"DELAY" LINK Arg_Delay} tooltype until the
animations are started after the background picture has loaded.

